article.description: Teresa Edwards scored 18 points and the Minnesota Lynx snapped a two-game losing streak with a 64-61 victory over the Seattle Storm on Friday night.
article.headline: Minnesota snaps two-game skid
article.linkText: Lynx top Storm, move into third in the West
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Veteran Teresa Edwards carried the Minnesota
Lynx in one of their biggest games of the season.

The 40-year-old Edwards scored 18 points, and the Lynx snapped a
two-game losing streak with a 64-61 victory over the Seattle Storm
on Friday night.

Edwards, a former Olympic teammate of Minnesota coach Suzie
McConnell Serio in 1988 and 1992, shot 6-for-9 from the field,
including 3-for-4 from the 3-point arc, and added five rebounds and
three steals. After averaging 16.9 minutes per game since July 1,
Edwards -- who turned 40 on July 19 -- played 30 minutes on Friday
and was a commanding presence on the floor.

"There were times when she looked like the old 'T' I used to
play with," McConnell Serio said. "We were looking for leadership
and experience from our veterans, and Teresa Edwards took it
personally to step up and respond."

The Lynx solidified their hold on third place in the Western
Conference, trailing second-place Seattle by one game with four to
play. Any combination of three wins by Minnesota and losses by
fifth-place Sacramento will put the Lynx in the playoffs for the
second straight year.

"This league is very competitive this year, and it's anybody's
championship," Edwards said. "We really believe in our chances to
win it."

Helen Darling added a career-high 10 assists for the Lynx, while
Nicole Ohlde scored 16 points, Svetlana Abrosimova added 11 and
Tamika Williams finished with 10 for Minnesota.

Sue Bird led the Storm with 15 points, and Lauren Jackson added
12 for Seattle, which is within a victory of securing a playoff
berth.

The game featured three long scoring streaks before a tight
finish. Seattle had runs of 17-3 and 17-5 around a 17-0 Minnesota
outburst and took a 59-55 lead with less than two minutes
remaining.

But after a three-point play by Abrosimova, Lynx rookie center
Ohlde put Minnesota ahead for good at 60-59 with an up-and-under
move against Jackson down low that impressed the reigning league
MVP.

"Nicole Ohlde is a really good player," said Jackson, who was
held 8.4 points below her league-leading scoring average. "Some of
the things she does remind me of myself. She's very strong inside,
something you wouldn't expect by looking at her."

From there, the teams traded free throws until Seattle trailed
by three with time for one last possession. Betty Lennox got a
clear look at the basket, but missed a 3-pointer, giving Minnesota
its first win in three games against Seattle this season.

"Against Detroit two days ago, I felt we had our focus and our
fight the whole game," Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "And then
tonight, only two days later, to not have that same focus and fight
is extremely frustrating for me. We are fighting for our playoff
lives, and this team played with no sense of urgency."
